I"Ä<p>Consider these two numbers: 5 out of 100 and 5%. They are the same, just expressed differently. The first number is expressed as a relative frequency and the second number is expressed as a probability in percentage format. It turns out people perceive them differently when putting them into a context. Consider the following two statements about the chance that a mental patient commits an act of violence within 6 months after discharge<sup id="fnref:1" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote" rel="footnote">1</a></sup>:</p>

